⚖️ LCES: Legal Calculus Educational System

LCES is a serious attempt to turn legal disorder into disciplined sequence.

🟦 Isolate the issue

🟩 Anchor the facts

🟨 Define the objective

🟧 Research before drafting

🟥 Separate drafting from critique

🟪 Treat preservation as part of the remedy

In the context of the justice gap, self-represented litigants, and AI-assisted filing, this is a timely idea.

LCES deserves attention as:

🔹 A procedural-literacy model

🔹 A teaching framework

🔹 A clinic workflow

🔹 A record-first method

🔹 A way to reduce confusion before action

But the evidence also matters.

LCES should not be presented as a proven substitute for licensed counsel or mature access-to-justice infrastructure.

🟦 What still needs validation?

🧪 User comprehension

📄 Filing quality

✅ Task completion

🚫 Rejection rates

♿ Accessibility

🗂️ Preservation completeness

⚖️ Downstream outcomes

The fairest conclusion:

LCES is a promising workflow architecture and educational framework.

It is not yet a fully validated, court-integrated system.

That distinction matters.

Because procedural literacy is not just about acting.

It is about acting in a way that is structured, reviewable, and capable of surviving the legal system’s own mechanic